In vitro experiments using the bending bile duct with corner pockets model (
Fig. 2
) revealed that counterclockwise rotation exhibited superior efficacy in removing debris and stones. While sweeping with clockwise rotation, debris was scraped out by the basket; however, residual debris was significant. On the other hand, during counterclockwise sweeps, debris scraped by the basket wires was observed to collect and accumulate within the basket lumen, facilitating en masse removal (
Fig. 3
). Although a balloon catheter could release stones lodged in the bile duct flexure and corner pockets, the 8-wire helical basket with a counterclockwise rotation demonstrated the ability to retrieve lodged stones even from the corner pocket of the CBD terminus (
Fig. 4
).
